Anonymous Thu 07 Jan 2021 23:50:14 No.35340225 Report
Quoted By:
>>35339739
To add on, write the story you want to tell.
Will a gentle femdom story with a unremarkable Anon and a FOTW/M anthro get lots of attention? Yes, but if you're not up to the task of a firehose worth of opinion s then you'll quit halfway through.
On the other hand, if you write something out of the usual genres (scifi/fantasy or SoL) 90% of the thread might not leave their individual comfort zones.
On the gripping hand, beating your head against the wall over what anyone else (or you, for that matter) thinks just leads to a concussion.

Writing isn't some always inspired ball of fun.
But when you have an idea, don't let it (and her!) die due to apathy and neglect.

Anonymous Fri 08 Jan 2021 02:07:31 No.35343967 Report
Quoted By:
>>35343771
I've been keeping track of open projects in a spreadsheet. My goal is 500k words of first draft for the year. This works out to a little over 1k a day, assuming I write daily. Weekends are double since I'm off from work.

The real trick I'm trying to make habit is finding a stopping point where I can think about next day's writing. Then I sit down prepared to do something.
If I'm not feeling sharp? What haven't I given attention lately? Let's look over that first pass and add some detail.

Nothing more than making it a regular thing. You get good at lifting weights if you hit them regularly and with purpose, but without pushing yourself to injury.
Same idea.
Avoid extreme burnout, realize every paragraph counts.
